===Etymology 3===
<!--Someone please verify this word-->
Corruption of the Latin ''[[aeger]]'' ("ill").
====Adjective====
'''wag'''
# [[pretending]] to be [[ill]]. Also 'wagging it large'

====Verb====
{{en-verb|wag|wags|wagged|wagging}}
# (''British slang'') To [[pretend]] to be [[ill]] in order to [[shirk]] a [[responsibility]], usually school lessons
# (''slang'') To not go to school, either for a class or classes or the entire school day<sup>1</sup> (c.f. <span style="font-variant:small-caps;text-transform:lowercase">play the wag; hop the wag</span>)
:*"My misfortunes all began in ''wagging,'' Sir; but what could I do, exceptin' ''wag''?" "Excepting what?" said Mr. Carker. "''Wag,'' Sir. ''Wagging'' from school." "Do you mean pretending to go there, and not going?" said Mr. Carker. "Yes, Sir, that's ''wagging,'' Sir." <br>-- Charles Dickens, ''Dombey and Son,'' xxii, (1848)
:*They had "''wagged'' it" from school, as they termed it, which..meant truancy in all its forms. -- William Sylvester Walker, ''In the Blood,''<br>i. 13 (1901)

